\section{Estimation of Population Mean}

What if we DO NOT KNOW the population mean or it's distribution?

\begin{itemize} 
\item the population mean $\mu$ is estimated using the sample mean $\bar{X}$.

\item This estimate tend to miss by an amount called the {\bf{standard error (SE)}} of the mean, which is calculated as 

\begin{equation} 
SE = \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} \nonumber 
\end{equation}
\item (Note: $s$ is the sample standard deviation).
\end{itemize}

Let's examine this idea using the following examples.

What is the average length of stay for an undergraduate student at WMU?

\begin{enumerate}
\item Suppose 25 graduating students were randomly selected and asked about their length of stay.  Suppose that the sample averaged 5.3 years, with a standard deviation of 1.5 years.  Then the WMU average stay is estemated as \underline{\phantom{xxxxxxxxx}} years give or take \underline{\phantom{xxxxxxxxx}} years or so.

\begin{align*}
\bar{X} &= 5.3  \\
SE &= \frac{1.5}{\sqrt{25}} = 0.3
\end{align*}

\item A second sample of 100 students were interviewed.  The mean and standard deviation for the second sample were 5.3 years and 1.5 years, respectively.  Calculate an estimate for the WMU average stay and provide a standard error for your estimate. 

\begin{align*}
\bar{X} &= 5.3  \\
SE &= \frac{1.5}{\sqrt{100}} = 0.15
\end{align*}
\end{enumerate}


